@44  = ~Minsc, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@45  = ~On second thought, Minsc, I want you to stay with the group.~
@46  = ~Let evil beware, lest it get a righteous boot betwixt the eyes! Onward!~
@47  = ~All right, <CHARNAME>. Minsc and Boo shall wait for you here.~
@48  = ~All right, <CHARNAME>. Minsc (and Boo), and his witch, shall wait for you here.~
@49  = ~Boo and I were about to leave anyway! I have never seen such behavior in all my days! And you claim to be heroes? Good riddance!~
@50  = ~Boo and I were about to leave anyway! I have never seen such behavior in all my days! And you claim to be heroes? Good riddance! Come Dynaheir, I will not feel good about your safety until we are away from here.~
@51  = ~Minsc might look simple, but he has Boo. And Boo would never let him wait here. No sir.~
@52  = ~Minsc might look simple, but he has Boo. And Boo would never let him wait here. No sir. Minsc has to protect his witch.~
@53  = ~Minsc and Boo shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. It's a good place to get ready for some serious butt-kicking!~
@54  = ~When in Baldur's Gate, Minsc (and Boo) go to the Elfsong tavern. We'll be there when you are ready to whip the scrambled eggs of evilness with righteous steel!~
@55  = ~We shall all wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. It's a good place to get ready for some serious butt-kicking!~
@56  = ~When in Baldur's Gate, Minsc (and Boo), and their witch, go to the Elfsong tavern. We'll be there when you are ready to whip the scrambled eggs of evilness with righteous steel!~
@57  = ~Skie, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@58  = ~On second thought, Skie, I want you to stay with the group.~
@59  = ~Thank you so much! I was so scared. This is nothing like life in the city.~
@60  = ~Yeah... I guess I don't have a choice.~
@61  = ~Yeah... I guess I don't have a choice. Eldoth, please don't leave me now.~
@62  = ~Fine! I was going to leave soon anyway! You're really not the kind of people I should be travelling with.~
@63  = ~Fine! I was going to leave soon anyway! You're really not the kind of people I should be travelling with. Eldoth is better company than you.~
@64  = ~Why are you asking this of me, <CHARNAME>? I can't stay alone in this place, I'll die of fright!~
@65  = ~Why are you asking this of me, <CHARNAME>? I can't stay in this place, even with Eldoth, I'll die of fright!~
@66  = ~I... I suppose I can go to Feldepost's Inn in Beregost and wait for you there. I still have a few coins. But hurry up, please? I... I can't bear to be alone!~
@67  = ~Father once said that the Elfsong tavern is a good place. I... I suppose I can stay there for a while.~
@68  = ~I... I suppose we can go to Feldepost's Inn in Beregost and wait for you there. We still have a few coins, don't we, Eldoth?~
@69  = ~Father once said that the Elfsong tavern is a good place. I... I suppose we can stay there for a while. Will you go there with me, Eldoth?~
@70  = ~Eldoth, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@71  = ~On second thought, Eldoth, I want you to stay with the group.~
@72  = ~I thought as much. Lead on, and wake me up whenever we get wherever it is we are going.~
@73  = ~Indeed, <CHARNAME>. I might wait for you here if I decide it is worth my time.~
@74  = ~Indeed, <CHARNAME>. We might wait for you here if I decide it is worth my time. Come, Skie.~
@75  = ~I would rather travel alone than spend a second more with you boorish oafs. Goodbye, and good riddance.~
@76  = ~I would rather travel alone than spend a second more with you boorish oafs. Goodbye, and good riddance. Come along, Skie.~
@77  = ~Do you take me for a complete nincompoop, <CHARNAME>? I would not linger here for all the treasures of Balduran.~
@78  = ~Do you take me for a complete nincompoop, <CHARNAME>? We would not linger here for all the treasures of Balduran. Besides, I have business to complete.~
@79  = ~Well, I can sometimes be found at Feldepost's Inn of Beregost. It is a place with at least some hint of civilization. Not that I promise to be there, mind you.~
@80  = ~When in Baldur's Gate, one should naturally visit the Elfsong tavern. That place has at the least heard of mulled Arabellan Red.~
@81  = ~Well, I can sometimes be found at Feldepost's Inn of Beregost. It is a place with at least some hint of civilization. Not that I promise to be there, mind you. Don't simper, Skie. I hate simpering. Of course you are going with me.~
@82  = ~Xzar, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@83  = ~On second thought, Xzar, I want you to stay with the group.~
@84  = ~Hurrah! I'd have us all sing with joy, but I'm sure such an outpouring would come dangerously close to making me sick. Onward, and all that.~
@85  = ~Fine, <CHARNAME>. I shall pine away the days on this very spot waiting for you to return. Wheeeee.~
@86  = ~Fine, <CHARNAME>. Monty and I shall pine away the days on this very spot waiting for you to return. Wheeeee.~
@87  = ~Indeed, it is quite about time that we should part company. You have proven unsympathetic to my interests, and I look forward to eventually owning a charming little ashtray made from your skull. Toodles.~
@88  = ~Indeed, it is quite about time that we should part company. You have proven unsympathetic to my interests, and I look forward to eventually owning a charming little ashtray made from your skull. Come, Montaron. We shall not be separated by this fool.~
@89  = ~Now, I might be insane, but I am not a fool. <CHARNAME>, I would not wait here for all the chattering skulls of the City of Doors. (No one truly knows if such a place exists, but still...)~
@90  = ~Now, I might be insane, but I am not a fool. <CHARNAME>, Monty and I would not wait here for all the chattering skulls of the City of Doors. (No one truly knows if such a place exists, but still...)~
@91  = ~Tee-hee. See if you can find your way to the dragon's lair before I grow bored of waiting. I had better hurry though, the hedgehog awaits.~
@92  = ~They say fish can't talk, but it sure is more entertaining than flying pigs. My time will be better spent chatting with eels at the bottom of the sea.~
@93  = ~Tee-hee. See if you can find your way to the dragon's lair, before we grow bored of waiting. Come, Monty, the hedgehog awaits.~
@94  = ~They say fish can't talk, but it sure is more entertaining than flying pigs. Come, Montaron, our time will be better spent chatting with eels at the bottom of the sea.~
@95  = ~Montaron, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@96  = ~On second thought, Montaron, I want you to stay with the group.~
@97  = ~A wise choice, indeed. Puts off me having to kill you by a few days at least.~
@98  = ~Suit yerself, <CHARNAME>. I shall wait for ye here.~
@99  = ~Suit yerself, <CHARNAME>. We shall wait for ye here. Don't fret over yer bootlaces, wizard! And stop *drooling* at me!~
@100 = ~And good riddance to yer, bad rubbish! I suggest ye sleep with one eye open from now on.~
@101 = ~And good riddance to yer, bad rubbish! I suggest ye sleep with one eye open from now on. Come wizard! I'll not miss yer inevitable death by leavin' ye behind!~
@102 = ~D'ye think I'm stupid, <CHARNAME>? I would not stay here for a steam bath full of naked elven virgins!~
@103 = ~D'ye think we are stupid, <CHARNAME>? We would not stay here for a steam bath full of naked elven virgins!~
@104 = ~Nashkel's Belching Dragon is my kind of a place. See if ye can find your way down there, before I get bored of waiting.~
@105 = ~There still be a few interestin' places left in Baldur's Gate. The Low Lantern is a cozy bordello disguised as a boat. Seek me out there. Ye won't be sorry.~
@106 = ~Nashkel's Belching Dragon is our kind of a place. See if ye can find your way down there, before we get bored of waiting.~
@107 = ~There still be a few interestin' places in Baldur's Gate. The Low Lantern is a cozy bordello disguised as a boat. Seek us out there. Ye won't be sorry.~
@108 = ~Edwin, ich möchte, dass wir für einige Zeit trennen. Warte einfach hier auf mich. Ich werde zurückkehren, wenn ich Eure Hilfe benötige.~ 
@109 = ~Ich habs mir anders überlegt, Edwin, ich möchte, dass Ihr in meiner Gruppe bleibt.~
@110 = ~Spart Euch Eure Höflichkeiten. (Ich erdulde diese Gruppe voller Idioten nur, weil einigermaßen nützlich erscheinen.)~ 
@111 = ~Gute Befreiung. (Und ich bin noch nicht verstoßen worden, ich... ich habe nur darauf gewartet, ich werde mir meine wohlverdiente Ruhe gönnen, abseits von diesen... diesen nervtötenden... Affen! Ja! Das ist das richtige Wort.)~
@112 = ~Ihr verstößt mich, als ob ich ein einfacher Diener wäre? (Für diese Unverfrorenheit werden sie bezahlen!)~ 
@113 = ~Haltet Ihr mich für einen Volltrottel, Aff... äh <CHARNAME>? (Diese Tölpel werden niemals ein wahres Genie zu schätzen wissen, selbst wenn er ihnen auf einem Silbertablett serviert werden würde.) Ich würde nicht in dieser ekelhaften Kloake bleiben, das ist nur etwas für einen Haufen kranker Schimpansen, nicht einmal für alle Schätze von Thay. (Und das sind *wirklich* viele goldene Münzen, das könnt Ihr mir glauben.)~
@114 = ~Nashkel's Belching Dragon is a nauseous, filthy pigsty. But it will have to do. See if you can find your way down there, before I grow bored of waiting. (Let's see how quickly they will discover my irreplaceability. I bet they will run all the way down to Nashkel.)~
@115 = ~There are yet some sumptuous places in the squalid collection of hovels that they call Baldur's Gate. The Low Lantern is a splendid Hell disguised as a boat. Seek me out there when you grow bored of your petty pursuits. (Not that these simians would appreciate true splendor if it came up to them and bit them.)~
@116 = ~Shar-Teel, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@117 = ~On second thought, Shar-Teel, I want you to stay with the group.~
@118 = ~Make no mistake; I follow you only because of your prowess in battle. When that falters, so does my loyalty.~
@119 = ~Agreed for now. But don't dawdle!~
@120 = ~Ah, I'm finally released from this infernal duty! I swear by every god in a million pantheons that I will NEVER lose a duel to another overly masculine thug in my life.~
@121 = ~Do you take me for a brainless idiot, <CHARNAME>? I would not stay here for all the treasures of Balduran. ~
@122 = ~I will wait for you in Nashkel's Belching Dragon. Don't dawdle though. I won't stay there for long!~
@123 = ~I will wait for you in the Blushing Mermaid. A filthy place, but it will have to do.~
@124 = ~Tiax, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@125 = ~On second thought, Tiax, I want you to stay with the group.~
@126 = ~Your continuing delusion of leadership will serve Tiax well in the long run. Lead on for now, but eventually Tiax rules!~
@127 = ~Yes, yes, the all-seeing Tiax thinks that this spot is best suited for refining his ideas of world domination.~
@128 = ~What?! You galley-whipped short-knickers! Tiax the Grand will not stand to be cast aside! He shall ascend without your bumbling sneakery! The Great Tiax, betrayed on all sides by those seeking to undermine his coming rule, casts aside the refuse he once called his slaves! Mindless fools! Breathe deep and fill your ill-fated lungs with the salty air of your sorry destiny!~
@129 = ~Do you take Tiax for a short-sighted fool, by chance? Great Tiax cannot wait here. This measly place is unsuitable for his majestic grandeur, and no self-respecting ruler of the world would set up court here. The Weapons of Merciless Doom may have even been stored here by his Enemies for all he knows!~
@130 = ~Let it be known that for the next few days Tiax the Grand will receive petitioners and seekers of his favor in Nashkel's Belching Dragon.~
@131 = ~Sidekicks and slaves, cease your pointless simpering, for the Dark Overlord of Toril and its Adjacent Planes, Tiax the Grand, is leaving this measly location for the city of Baldur's Gate! The Grand Palace of the Blushing Mermaid will serve as a residence.~
@132 = ~Viconia, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@133 = ~On second thought, Viconia, I want you to stay with the group.~
@134 = ~I could ask for little else.~
@135 = ~Agreed. I shall hide myself nearby, until you return.~
@136 = ~A welcome release. Your weakling surface ways have left a bitter taste in my mouth. Perhaps I should seek shelter back under the cover of the earth. I understood my fellows there.~
@137 = ~Do not mock me, surfacer! I cannot wait for you here. This place brings back memories... those of the more *unpleasant* kind.~
@138 = ~Whilst travelling along the Nashkel Road, I spotted a nice, dry cave that would do as a short-term abode. Perchance you could seek me out there, when you are ready to take me with you?~
@139 = ~I suppose I could wait for you in the Blushing Mermaid... I despise the place, but there, even a drow can blend with the crowd... at least for a while.~
@140 = ~Kagain, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@141 = ~On second thought, Kagain, I want you to stay with the group.~
@142 = ~Straight to the point, I respect that. Let's go.~
@143 = ~Aye, <CHARNAME>. I'll be 'round here somewheres.~
@144 = ~Heh, my reputation's probably calmed down by now, anyway. See ya around, ya lumps.~
@145 = ~Are yer taking me fer a fool, <CHARNAME>? I'll not wait here for all of Balduran's gold! ~
@146 = ~I'll go back to me shop then. Find me when yer through floundering and want to do some serious business.~
@147 = ~I can wait fer yer in the Blushing Mermaid. Their wares ain't on the cheap side, if yer gettin my drift, but at least they don't water down their ale with cat's piss. Har Har.~
@148 = ~Ajantis, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@149 = ~On second thought, Ajantis, I want you to stay with the group.~
@150 = ~As it should be! Let us go!~
@151 = ~As you command, <CHARNAME>. I shall wait.~
@152 = ~<CHARNAME>, a responsible leader would not cast aside a worthy blade on a mere flight of fancy. It is about time that we parted ways.~
@153 = ~<CHARNAME>, I cannot just idle my time away here, awaiting your return! Evil lurks in every shadow, begging to be cleansed.~
@154 = ~But... but... we were a team, we were bound by... by honor! Sigh... <CHARNAME>, I would rather stay with you, but if you insist... I will be waiting for you at the Friendly Arm Inn.~
@155 = ~But... but... we were a team, we were bound by... by honor! Sigh... Prelate Wesselan once mentioned that the Elfsong tavern is a good place to start looking for adventure.~
@156 = ~Quayle, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@157 = ~On second thought, Quayle, I want you to stay with the group.~
@158 = ~Of course you need me! You would be a complete and utter moron if you didn't think so! Lead on.~
@159 = ~Hmph, I might just do it, you know. I mean, yeah, I'll wait.~
@160 = ~Hmph! You are superfluous to my well being and I can't say I'll miss being confronted with your Orcish face and Troll-like breath each morning! Good riddance to stupid rubbish!~
@161 = ~Do you take me for a complete gull, <CHARNAME>? How can I stay here alone even for a moment? Do you hear buzzards? I hear buzzards!~
@162 = ~I shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn then. It is the perfect place, safe from buzzards and all. Ain't cheap though, uh-huh, anything but cheap.~
@163 = ~Hmph, I can wait for you in the Elfsong tavern, I suppose. Nice, crowded kind of a place. Ain't cheap though, uh-huh, anything but cheap.~
@164 = ~Garrick, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@165 = ~On second thought, Garrick, I want you to stay with the group.~
@166 = ~We are surely at the beginning of an epic tale. Lead on!~
@167 = ~Of course, <CHARNAME>! I'll wait for you here.~
@168 = ~You're no better than Ms. Silke! It will catch up with you, someday, mark my words.~
@169 = ~I... I am truly sorry to admit this, <CHARNAME>... But... but I cannot stay here without you! Not for all the treasures of Balduran.~
@170 = ~I shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. It is the perfect place for a vagabond poet, biding his time between adventures.~
@171 = ~I shall wait for you in the Elfsong tavern of Baldur's Gate. *blushes* The maid there was very friendly last time I asked for a glass of their cheapest wine...~
@172 = ~Imoen, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@173 = ~On second thought, Imoen, I want you to stay with the group.~
@174 = ~You bet! We'll nick ourselves a whole purse o' fun before the night is through!~
@175 = ~Of course, <CHARNAME>! You bet I'll wait for you. Just don't take too long. Pretty pleeease?~
@176 = ~Well, good! You've changed since we were friends anyway. Not nearly as much fun now. Should have stayed in Candlekeep, instead of wasting time with you gully pennies.~
@177 = ~You aren't going to abandon me here, are you? I cannot stay in this place all alone.~
@178 = ~All right, no problem here. I'll wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. Don't take too long though. (laughs) I'll miss you and all that stuff...~
@179 = ~All right, no problem here. I'll wait for you in the Elfsong tavern. Don't take too long though. (laughs) I'll miss you and all that stuff...~
@180 = ~Xan, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@181 = ~On second thought, Xan, I want you to stay with the group.~
@182 = ~Then I shall do my best for you, though I am sure we both know that the worst is inevitable.~
@183 = ~No doubt some untenable disaster will befall me the moment you walk away. Hopefully my bleached bones will remain here to tell the tale.~
@184 = ~This whole mission has been a dismal failure from the very start. Consider my debt repaid, friends, as I certainly do.~
@185 = ~The dismal failure of this whole operation is inevitable, whether I stay here or not. Yet wooing one's doom seems excessive, to say the least.~
@186 = ~I shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn then. No doubt the place will burn to the ground the moment I set my foot inside.~
@187 = ~I will go to the Elfsong tavern then. By all odds it will be washed away by a flood, or destroyed by an earthquake.~
@188 = ~Branwen, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@189 = ~On second thought, Branwen, I want you to stay with the group.~
@190 = ~I welcome your company, as I always do.~
@191 = ~I owe you much, <CHARNAME>. Surely, I will do your bidding.~
@192 = ~You are no more honorable than the Loki spawn I left behind!~
@193 = ~<CHARNAME>, this place is unsafe. Why challenge my friendship with such a severe test?~
@194 = ~I can certainly do that. <CHARNAME>, I shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. ~
@195 = ~Sure enough. <CHARNAME>, I will be in the Elfsong tavern when you need me again.~
@196 = ~Alora, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@197 = ~On second thought, Alora, I want you to stay with the group.~
@198 = ~Oh goody good good! Let's go!~
@199 = ~Then I guess I have no choice but to wait. Sniff...~
@200 = ~If that's the way you want it, then fine, I'll leave! Sniff...~
@201 = ~Do you think I'm daft? I'll not wait here for all the gold in the world!~
@202 = ~I shall go to the Friendly Arm Inn then. Sniff. Bentley talks tough, but he really is a softie. Most of the fatcats that stay there are complete gulls.~
@203 = ~I'll be in the Elfsong then. Not many elves there, really, but plenty of lunkheads with full pockets.~
@204 = ~Yeslick, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@205 = ~On second thought, Yeslick, I want you to stay with the group.~
@206 = ~A wise move. Together we can't possibly fail.~
@207 = ~So be it, <CHARNAME>. I'll wait.~
@208 = ~Fine, I'll be leaving the likes of you, then. This party's been just another prison for me.~
@209 = ~<CHARNAME>, I've not escaped prison to be led into a rattrap and left behind. A true friend wouldn't test his comrades' mettle with such tricks!~
@210 = ~Then I'll wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn. My nephew used to work for the Mirrorshades, they are a decent folk.~
@211 = ~I can wait for you in the Elfsong tavern of Baldur's Gate, I s'ppose. Not the best place for a dwarf, but I've seen far worse in my times.~
@212 = ~Faldorn, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@213 = ~On second thought, Faldorn, I want you to stay with the group.~
@214 = ~Together we shall enforce the laws of nature with the ruthless vigor they deserve.~
@215 = ~Very well, I shall wait here. Mind though that my patience is only as long-lasting as your eagerness to defend the Great Mother.~
@216 = ~Maybe this is for the best. I have no patience for your weaknesses.~
@217 = ~How can you ask me to linger in this unclean place, awaiting your return, when my rage can be spent on bettering the Nature's cause in her bullyragged glades and forests?~
@218 = ~If one day you would once again seek my assistance, look for me in the sacred forest of Cloakwood. Hurry up, though, for very soon the Great Mother might need my strength elsewhere.~
@219 = ~I cannot tolerate the noise and filthy stench of cities. If one day you would once again seek my assistance, look for me in the sacred forest of Cloakwood. Hurry up, though, for very soon the Great Mother might need my strength elsewhere.~
@220 = ~Kivan, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@221 = ~On second thought, Kivan, I want you to stay with the group.~
@222 = ~A wise choice. Lead on.~
@223 = ~Agreed. I shall wait.~
@224 = ~Certainly. I am glad to rid myself of such untrustworthy companionship.~
@225 = ~<CHARNAME>, I cannot wait for you here. My life is worth very little, but my vengeance cannot be postponed to appease your fancy. Tazok lives still.~
@226 = ~I shall wait for you at the Friendly Arm Inn then. Hurry up though, for my vengeance cannot be delayed for your sake.~
@227 = ~I shall wait for you in the Elfsong tavern then. Hurry up though, for my vengeance cannot be delayed for your sake.~
@228 = ~Coran, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@229 = ~On second thought, Coran, I want you to stay with the group.~
@230 = ~A wise choice, my friend!~
@231 = ~Sure, I can spend a few minutes dawdling here. Hurry up though, for Lady Luck frowns upon the slothful and the dull.~
@232 = ~You want us to part ways now, just like that? I should have known not to have joined you in the first place.~
@233 = ~Do you take me for a fool, <CHARNAME>? *whistles* I follow your orders, but only when they are sane.~
@234 = ~A friendly lass on my lap and a glass of decent wine in my hand... *laughs* Sounds like the perfect way to spend a stormy afternoon! You've got yourself a deal, <CHARNAME>. I'll wait for you in Nashkel's Belching Dragon.~
@235 = ~A friendly lass on my lap and a glass of decent wine in my hand... *laughs* Sounds like the perfect way to spend a chilly morning! You've got yourself a deal, <CHARNAME>. I'll wait for you in the Elfsong tavern.~
@236 = ~Safana, I do not want to part ways with you forever. Just wait for me here. I will return for you when I need your help again.~
@237 = ~On second thought, Safana, I want you to stay with the group.~
@238 = ~Certainly. Lead and I shall follow.~
@239 = ~I'll wait, but do not linger. As I said, I have my own way of looking at things.~
@240 = ~Hmm, it seems that all northerners are as mindless as they are impotent. Do as you wish, I will find my own way.~
@241 = ~No, <CHARNAME>. I shall definitely not wait for you here. This place is too dangerous to linger in alone.~
@242 = ~Fine. You can try looking for me in Nashkel's Belching Dragon. Not that I promise to be there, mind you.~
@243 = ~Fine. You can try looking for me in the Elfsong tavern. Not that I promise to be there, mind you.~
@244 = ~I will fight you to mine last breath, Vremoni!~
@245 = ~Butt - kicking For GOODNESS! RAAAAARGH!~
